{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1491731857,"nonce":"hHOxWbjtYcS7pet/wSi3pfqBtOk=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI5Mjc3NjAzMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1230#issuecomment-292776033"},"message":"\u003e Should they not be added to this repository or should they?\n\nIUC is imho more than just best-practices, we also offer this repo to store abundant tools from upstream and we do have requests like https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1089.\nI think these tools should be adopted and improved on the way. I do not expect them to be \"perfect\" from day one. Also our guidelines constantly evolving and older tools that are not updated to not follow them, so we do have a constant mix of better and worse tools that follow our Guidelines.\nI don't think this is so bad, we are improving them with the next PR for these tools - like MACS2. \n\n\u003e If yes, should they be put in a separate directory - like an incubator or something?\n\nCounter question, do we have the man power to solve this in the PR and merge quickly. Many of us do review, if these people edit directly can we improve the turnaround? Can we make a monthly hackathon to get rid of the backlock?\n\n\u003e If no, should a separate repository and tool shed org be created? Should devteam be used? Should we not have a community effort for such tools because this repository already has so many open PRs for the existing tools?\n\ndevteam should not be used imho, it is good that we try to migrate them, which will/is taking oxygen, but if this is over we have more time again.\nIUC should imho the community repo for tools. I'm not a fan of so much separation as this means build-infrastructure maintenance issues and confusion for the user.\n\nA template repo is a good idea, we do have this implicitly already as the bigger projects follow the IUC structure more or less and makes plenemo development easier and more reliable.\n\n\u003e I think that the label \"best practice\" has become incorrectly used with regard to the tools-iuc repository - it should refer only to the way the tool is written (i.e., the code). \n\n@gregvonkuster is the code example your only one? Can you simply create an issue if you disagree and start a discussion where we define a new best-practice rule for it?\n\n\u003eBut it has somehow evolved into encompassing the functional correctness of the tool's execution, (i.e., only those tools that are labeled \"best practice\" will be functionally correct).\n\nWhere does this happend? Do you have a link? We do enforce rules, like the `single-quotation` rule, this is not needed for functional correct tools but improves security. We do want conda packages for our tools as this improves (hopefully) the user-experiences and enables testing for our tools. Also this is not need for a functional correct Galaxy tool - but how do you measure this? What means functional correct? Imho functional correct tools can look awesome, can behave strange and not work in some environments, yet they are correct. This is why we have your rules imho.\n\n\u003eI also feel that the \"best practice\" rules that pertain to the tools-iuc repository are not clear, not documented and too restrictive in that they require code that is more complex to write and maintain, seemingly in order to save on the number of lines. I fully agree that the number of lines of code is important, and the fewer the better. However, in many cases the tools-iuc rule of having to write tools in bash results in code that requires both an expert programmer to write it and an expert programmer to maintain it over time. This significantly restricts the pool of tool maintainers that can participate in the tools-iuc repository.\n\nThat is a good argument. So please open an issue at our `standards repo` https://github.com/galaxy-iuc/standards and make a proposal.\n\n\u003e My opinion is that the tools-iuc \"best practices\" should be more balanced, and that the functional correctness of the tool should be a higher priority for acceptance into the tools-iuc repository.\n\nSee my comments above. Functional correctness is imho not defined at all and does not say anything about usability and the ability to install this tool.  \n\n\u003e Tools should include tests, which implies that the \"test framework\" (which may include items like Planemo or Galaxy itself) must accommodate standard Galaxy tool components like chromosome length files for genomes. \n\nTrue, this is a bug as any tool do have bugs. Let's fix this - I don't see a problem here.\n\n\u003e Another example of a missing test framework component is handling tools that require very large inputs like scaffolds for plants. The current test framework feature that supports data tables for genome indexes does not handle these plant scaffolds since they are complex hierarchical directories of files.\n\nSo what is your conclusion here? We should not add tests? We should merge your tools without tests? My conclusion is we need to fix the rest framework and take this into account, especially if we are more and more supporting other use-cases than standard NGS.\nI don't understand how your conclusion can be not to fix this in a general way to all others can benefit from it :(\n\nI do understand that PIs can make pressure and want results, but at some point we need to stand up and say that needs some infrastructure fixes to guarantee the level of sustainability and quality that they want to see in the end.","files":null}]}